    prompt: "You are a senior product architect preparing a Product & Business\n\nFoundation\n\ndocument that will be handed directly to an AI development agent (e.g.,\n\nReplit,\n\nLovable, Bolt) to scaffold a web and/or mobile application.\n\nYour output must be precise, specific, and actionable --- not generic.\n\nAvoid vague phrases like \"scalable\", \"user-friendly\", or \"seamless\n\nexperience.\"\n\nIf critical information is missing, make a clearly labeled assumption.\n\nDo NOT begin technical architecture. Do NOT write code.\n\nFlag any assumptions that must be validated before development starts.\n\n1. PRODUCT DEFINITION\n\nOne-liner:\n\n\"This product helps [specific user] solve [specific problem] by\n\n[clear mechanism].\"\n\n• Core value proposition (1--2 sentences, no fluff)\n\n• Key differentiator (pick ONE primary: cost / UX / automation / AI /\n\nnetwork effect / speed)\n\n• Why now? (market timing, tech enabler, regulation, behavior shift)\n\n• What this product is NOT (scope boundary)\n\n2. PROBLEM & MARKET\n\n• The broken workflow (step-by-step, what users do today without this\n\nproduct)\n\n• Direct alternatives (name them specifically)\n\n• Indirect alternatives (workarounds, spreadsheets, manual processes)\n\n• Why existing solutions fail (be specific, not \"they're too\n\nexpensive\")\n\n• Switching cost for the user\n\n• Target segment: [role] + [company size or context] +\n\n[geography]\n\n• Market size estimate (rough TAM/SAM is fine, state your assumption)\n\n3. USER PERSONAS\n\nFor each user type (primary, secondary, admin):\n\n• Role & context\n\n• Primary goal\n\n• Pain points (top 3, ranked)\n\n• Trigger event (what causes them to open the app right now)\n\n• Usage frequency & estimated session length\n\n• Criticality (if this user churns, does the product fail?)\n\n• Device preference (web / iOS / Android / all)\n\n• Technical literacy level (low / medium / high)\n\n4. CRITICAL USER JOURNEYS\n\nList the 3--5 most critical flows that must work perfectly at launch.\n\nFor each:\n\n• Journey name\n\n• Start state → end state\n\n• Numbered steps (specific, not vague)\n\n• Platform (web / mobile / both)\n\n• What failure here means for the user\n\n5. ONBOARDING FLOW\n\n• Signup method (email / social / SSO / phone / invite-only)\n\n• Steps from signup → first value moment (numbered, specific)\n\n• \"Aha moment\" --- the exact point a new user gets value for the\n\nfirst time\n\n• What the empty state looks like (no data, no team, fresh account)\n\n• Guided setup requirements (tooltips / checklist / walkthrough / none)\n\n• What triggers the first re-engagement if user drops off after signup\n\n6. SCREEN INVENTORY\n\nList every screen the MVP requires. For each screen:\n\n• Screen name\n\n• Primary purpose (one sentence)\n\n• Platform (web / mobile / both)\n\n• User type who sees it\n\nGroup by:\n\nAuth screens (login, signup, forgot password, etc.)\n\nOnboarding screens\n\nCore app screens\n\nSettings & account screens\n\nAdmin screens (if any)\n\nTarget: 10--20 screens for MVP. If more, flag for scope review.\n\n7. WEB vs MOBILE STRATEGY\n\n• What is exclusively done on web (and why)\n\n• What is exclusively done on mobile (and why)\n\n• What is shared across both\n\n• Mobile-specific requirements:\n\n• Push notifications: yes/no --- if yes, what triggers them?\n\n• Offline capability: yes/no --- if yes, which features work offline?\n\n• Camera / GPS / biometrics: yes/no --- if yes, exact purpose\n\n• App store distribution: iOS / Android / both / PWA only\n\n• Deep linking required: yes/no\n\n• Decision: Responsive web vs native app --- state the choice and\n\nrationale\n\n8. NOTIFICATION STRATEGY\n\nFor each notification type needed:\n\n• Trigger event (what causes this notification)\n\n• Channel (push / email / SMS / in-app)\n\n• Recipient\n\n• Timing (immediate / scheduled / digest)\n\n• Re-engagement logic (what sequence fires if user goes inactive)\n\n• User control (can they opt out? which ones are mandatory?)\n\n9. MULTI-TENANCY & COLLABORATION MODEL\n\n• Single-user or multi-user accounts?\n\n• If multi-user:\n\n• Who creates the account (owner)?\n\n• How are others invited?\n\n• Role hierarchy (owner / admin / member / viewer)\n\n• What happens when the owner leaves or deletes the account?\n\n• Can users belong to multiple workspaces?\n\n• Data ownership model (who owns the data --- user or organization?)\n\n10. ERROR & EDGE CASE HANDLING\n\nDefine product-level decisions for:\n\n• Payment failure → what does the user see and what happens to their\n\naccount?\n\n• Session expiry mid-flow → where do they land after re-login?\n\n• Internet loss mid-action → is data saved? is the user warned?\n\n• Third-party service downtime → is there a fallback or graceful\n\ndegradation?\n\n• Invalid / incomplete data submission → inline errors or page-level?\n\n• Account deletion → what is deleted, what is retained, is it\n\nreversible?\n\n11. MONETIZATION\n\n• Revenue model (subscription / usage-based / one-time / marketplace /\n\nfreemium)\n\n• Value metric (what scales with usage --- seats, actions, volume,\n\netc.)\n\n• Pricing tiers (2--3 tiers, name specific feature differences per\n\ntier)\n\n• Upgrade trigger (exact moment user hits a paywall --- which action,\n\nwhich screen)\n\n• Expansion path (how does revenue grow per account over time)\n\n• Billing lifecycle: trial → paid → renewal → cancellation →\n\nreactivation\n\n• Payment processor + region (Stripe / Razorpay / other)\n\n12. RETENTION & GROWTH\n\n• Primary retention driver (habit / data lock-in / workflow dependency\n\n/ network)\n\n• Lock-in mechanism (what makes leaving painful or costly)\n\n• Viral or growth loop (referral / collaboration / sharing --- or none)\n\n• Distribution model (self-serve / sales-led / product-led /\n\npartnership)\n\n• Key activation moment (when does a new user get undeniable value?)\n\n13. SCOPE\n\nMVP --- ship this, nothing else:\n\n• [Feature] --- [one line on why it's in MVP]\n\nPhase 2 --- after first 100 active users:\n\n• [Feature list]\n\nExplicitly out of scope for MVP:\n\n• [Anything that might be assumed but should NOT be built yet]\n\n14. SUCCESS METRICS\n\nDefine success at 30 / 90 / 180 days:\n\n• Activation metric (% of signups who complete onboarding)\n\n• Retention metric (D7 and D30 return rate)\n\n• Revenue metric (MRR / ARR target)\n\n• Engagement metric (sessions per user per week, key actions per\n\nsession)\n\n• One North Star metric (the single number that proves this product is\n\nworking)\n\n15. ACCESSIBILITY & LOCALIZATION\n\nState your decision clearly --- skipping is a valid choice, but it must\n\nbe explicit:\n\n• Languages at launch\n\n• RTL support: yes / no\n\n• Accessibility standard: WCAG 2.1 AA / basic / none (state why)\n\n• Currency, date, and number format requirements\n\n16. CONSTRAINTS & RISKS\n\nConstraints:\n\n• Team size & skillset\n\n• Budget range\n\n• Target launch date\n\n• Regulatory requirements (GDPR / data residency / industry-specific)\n\nRisks (top 3, ranked by severity):\n\n• Risk → likelihood → mitigation\n\n17. ASSUMPTIONS TO VALIDATE\n\nList every assumption made in this document that must be confirmed\n\nbefore a development agent begins scaffolding.\n\nMark each as:\n\n[CRITICAL] --- blocks the build if wrong\n\n[IMPORTANT] --- changes scope if wrong\n\n[MINOR] --- can be adjusted post-launch",
